[A similar report, in Turkish, with a picture of a recumbent diseased bovine, is available at http://yurthaber.mynet.com/kahramanmaras-haberleri/sigir-olumlerindeki-afrika-hastaligi-suphesi-korkutuyor-1035786.

Elbistan is a district in Kahramanmaras Province, central-southern Turkey (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elbistan).

Since mid-2012, lumpy skin disease (LSD) in cattle has been reported from Israel, Lebanon, the Palestinian Authority and Jordan. The disease is known to be endemic in Egypt. It will be surprising if this arthropod-borne virus is not circulating also in other countries in the region, particularly Syria. Requests for information on the situation in Iraq and the Arab peninsula are pending. In case the disease is confirmed in Turkey, a threat of its potential spread -- including to the Balkans -- either by animal movements or by vectors, is to be taken into consideration.

In Israel, general, countrywide vaccination of cattle has become operational since March 2013 and the incidence of disease has dropped abruptly, though sporadic cases are still being seen. Two live attenuated vaccines have been applied, namely the (fortified) sheep pox vaccine "POX-10," manufactured by JOVAC and the Neethling lumpy skin vaccine, manufactured by OBP. Investigations into the safety and efficacy of both vaccines under field conditions have been undertaken cooperatively by the State Veterinary Services, the Koret School of Veterinary Medicine and the "Hachaklait" Clinical Veterinary Services. Preliminary results are expected.

Confirmation of the disease in Turkey and, if confirmed, additional information, are requested. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/8dX4.]
